  </script>

  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why is it so hard to eat enough protein after 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most men over 40 struggle to hit their protein target for four specific reasons: breakfast is protein-poor by default (8–12g instead of 30g), lunch is convenience-based and often low in protein, snacks are nutritionally empty, and dinner gets overloaded in a way that doesn't compensate for earlier shortfalls. The result is a typical daily intake of 60–80 grams — roughly half of what most men over 40 actually need."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I start hitting 120 grams of protein per day?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The most reliable approach is fixing one meal at a time rather than overhauling everything at once. Start with breakfast — getting to 30g at meal one makes the rest of the day significantly easier. Then audit lunch for protein, replace one low-protein snack with cottage cheese or Greek yogurt, and keep dinner at 35–40g rather than trying to load the day's deficit into one meal."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a realistic daily protein intake for men over 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For men over 40, a realistic and research-supported daily protein target is 0.7–0.8 grams per pound of bodyweight. For a 180-pound man, that's roughly 125–145 grams per day. Most men are currently getting 60–80 grams — which feels adequate but leaves a 40–60 gram daily gap that compounds into meaningful muscle loss over months and years."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why does eating protein at dinner not make up for missing it earlier?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Due to anabolic resistance — the age-related reduction in muscle sensitivity to protein — older men cannot store excess protein from one meal to compensate for missed doses at earlier meals. Muscle protein synthesis requires a sufficient dose at each meal (30+ grams). Eating 70 grams at dinner triggers roughly the same muscle-building response as eating 35–40 grams, with the excess simply oxidized for energy."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the easiest way to add more protein to your diet after 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The highest-leverage changes for men over 40 are: (1) fix breakfast to hit 30g — Greek yogurt and eggs is the fastest option, (2) replace one low-protein snack with cottage cheese or Greek yogurt, (3) anchor lunch around a protein source rather than a carb. These three changes alone can close a 40–50 gram daily gap without changing dinner at all."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

