    <span class="eyebrow">Common Mistakes</span>
    <h1>Why It's So Hard to Hit 120g of Protein After 40<br /><em>(And How to Fix It)</em></h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Most men over 40 know they need more protein. Most still aren't hitting it. The problem isn't motivation — it's structure. Here's exactly where the day breaks down.</p>
    <p class="meta">SnapProtein · 7 min read</p>
  </div>

  <article class="article-wrap">

    <div class="quick-answer">
      <div class="qa-label">Short answer</div>
      <p>Most men over 40 fail to hit their protein target for four specific reasons: <strong>breakfast is protein-poor by default, lunch is convenience-based, snacks are nutritionally empty, and dinner gets overloaded in a way that doesn't actually compensate.</strong> The result is a typical daily intake of 60–80 grams — roughly half of what most men over 40 actually need. The fix is structural, not motivational.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      I spent years thinking I was eating enough protein. Training consistently, feeling fine, eating what felt like "a lot." When I finally tracked it, I was at 68 grams per day. I'm 200 pounds. The target was 140–160. I had a 70–90 gram daily gap — and I had no idea.
    </p>

    <p>
      That's not unusual. It's the norm. Most men over 40 who aren't hitting their protein target aren't failing because they don't care. They're failing because the structure of a typical day makes it almost impossible to get there without a plan.
    </p>

    <div class="killer-line">
      The problem isn't that 120 grams is too much.<br />It's that a typical day is designed to deliver about 65.
    </div>

    <p>Here's the gap in one glance:</p>

    <div style="background:var(--charcoal); border-radius:8px; padding:1.5rem 2rem; margin:2rem 0; display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr); gap:1rem; text-align:center;">
