        <div style="font-size:0.78rem; color:rgba(255,255,255,0.55); margin-top:4px;">daily gap, every day</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What a Typical Day Actually Looks Like</h2>

    <p>Before the fixes, it helps to see exactly where the gap comes from. This is a realistic day for most men over 40 — not a worst-case scenario. A normal day.</p>

    <div class="typical-day">
      <div class="td-label">The reality for most men over 40</div>
      <div class="td-headline">A Typical Day — Where the Gap Lives</div>

      <div class="td-row">
        <div class="td-meal">Breakfast</div>
        <div class="td-food">Cereal or toast + coffee</div>
        <div class="td-protein">8–10g</div>
      </div>
      <div class="td-row">
        <div class="td-meal">Lunch</div>
        <div class="td-food">Sandwich + chips or a fast food meal</div>
        <div class="td-protein">18–22g</div>
      </div>
      <div class="td-row">
        <div class="td-meal">Snack</div>
        <div class="td-food">Crackers, fruit, granola bar</div>
        <div class="td-protein">2–4g</div>
      </div>
      <div class="td-row">
        <div class="td-meal">Dinner</div>
        <div class="td-food">Chicken or beef with sides</div>
        <div class="td-protein">35–40g</div>
      </div>

      <div class="td-total">
        <span>Daily total</span>
        <span class="total-num">63–76g</span>
      </div>
      <div class="td-gap">50–60 grams short of the optimal target for most men over 40</div>
    </div>

    <p>
      That's not a bad day by most standards. It's what a reasonably health-conscious man over 40 actually eats. And it delivers roughly half the protein needed to support muscle maintenance — every single day.
    </p>

    <p>
      That daily shortfall compounds quietly. Not dramatically. No obvious symptoms in the short term. Just slow, gradual muscle loss that most men don't notice until it's already significant. That's exactly how <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/">sarcopenia progresses</a> — silently, across years, while everything feels normal.
    </p>

    <h2>The 4 Reasons the Day Breaks Down</h2>

    <p>The gap isn't random. It comes from the same four structural problems in almost every case.</p>

    <div class="problem-cards">

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div>
          <div class="problem-card-tag">Problem 1 · Morning</div>
          <div class="problem-card-name">Breakfast Is Protein-Poor by Default</div>
          <div class="problem-card-detail">The default Western breakfast — cereal, toast, juice, maybe a bagel — is carbohydrate-dominant. It tastes fine, it's convenient, and it delivers 8–12 grams of protein. You need 30. That 20-gram deficit before 9am sets the tone for the entire day.</div>
          <div class="problem-card-fix">→ Fix: One habit change at breakfast closes this gap entirely. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/high-protein-breakfast-men-over-40/" style="color:var(--green-dark);">See the 7 options that hit 30g+</a></div>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-card-grams">
          <div class="typical">~10g</div>
          <div class="typical-label">typical</div>
          <div class="target">30g</div>
          <div class="target-label">needed</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div>
          <div class="problem-card-tag">Problem 2 · Midday</div>
          <div class="problem-card-name">Lunch Is Convenience-Based, Not Protein-Based</div>
          <div class="problem-card-detail">Most men build lunch around convenience — whatever's fast, available, or easy to order. A sandwich, a wrap, a fast food combo. These meals can have 20 grams of protein or less. The protein is an afterthought. The carb or the convenience is the anchor.</div>
          <div class="problem-card-fix">→ Fix: Anchor lunch around protein first. Rotisserie chicken, canned tuna, or a turkey wrap built around the protein source — not around the bread.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-card-grams">
          <div class="typical">~20g</div>
          <div class="typical-label">typical</div>
          <div class="target">35g</div>
          <div class="target-label">needed</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div>
          <div class="problem-card-tag">Problem 3 · Afternoon</div>
          <div class="problem-card-name">Snacks Are a Protein Dead Zone</div>
          <div class="problem-card-detail">The average snack — crackers, fruit, a granola bar, a handful of nuts — delivers 2–5 grams of protein. It fills a hunger gap without contributing anything meaningful to your daily target. Most men over 40 have a snack slot in their day and waste it completely.</div>
          <div class="problem-card-fix">→ Fix: Replace one snack with cottage cheese (27g) or Greek yogurt (18g). This single swap adds 15–25 grams to your daily total with zero additional effort.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-card-grams">
          <div class="typical">~3g</div>
          <div class="typical-label">typical</div>
          <div class="target">25g</div>
          <div class="target-label">needed</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div>
          <div class="problem-card-tag">Problem 4 · Evening</div>
          <div class="problem-card-name">Dinner Gets Overloaded — and It Doesn't Help</div>
          <div class="problem-card-detail">Men who realize they're behind on protein try to fix the whole day at dinner. A massive chicken breast, a large steak, piling on the protein. The biology doesn't cooperate. Due to <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/" style="color:var(--text-muted);">anabolic resistance</a>, eating 70 grams at dinner triggers roughly the same muscle-building response as 35–40 grams. The excess is oxidized for energy, not stored as muscle.</div>
          <div class="problem-card-fix">→ Fix: Keep dinner at 35–40g and fix the earlier meals instead. The solution isn't a bigger dinner — it's a better morning.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-card-grams">
          <div class="typical">~38g</div>
          <div class="typical-label">typical</div>
          <div class="target">35–40g</div>
          <div class="target-label">optimal</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <h2>The Math Problem (This Is Why It Compounds)</h2>

    <p>
      Here's what makes the gap hard to see: each individual meal doesn't feel that far off. Breakfast at 10 grams doesn't feel like a disaster. Lunch at 20 grams seems reasonable. Dinner at 38 grams feels like a solid protein meal.
    </p>

    <p>
      But add them up and you're at 70 grams. The target for a 180-pound man is 125–145 grams. That's a 55–75 gram daily deficit — not from bad choices, just from a structure that was never designed around protein.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>The compounding problem:</strong> A 60-gram daily deficit means your muscles are operating protein-starved every single day. Over a month, that's 1,800 grams of missing protein. Over a year, it's the difference between maintaining muscle and losing it steadily — which is exactly what <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/" style="color:var(--green-dark);">anabolic resistance</a> makes worse with every passing year after 40.</p>
    </div>

    <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" class="related-post">
