    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>A note for the more advanced:</strong> For many men, 120g isn't the finish line — it's the floor. If you're training hard, over 190 pounds, or actively trying to build muscle, your target may be closer to 150–180g per day. But here's the reality: most men aren't missing by 10–20 grams. They're missing by 50+. That's why 120g is the number that matters first — and why closing that gap is the move before chasing anything higher.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

    <p>
      Hitting 120 grams of protein per day after 40 isn't hard because of willpower. It's hard because a default day — eating normally, without a plan — delivers about half that. The structure works against you until you change it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Four fixes. Start with breakfast. Add a real snack. Build lunch around protein. Stop loading dinner. Most men close a 50–60 gram daily gap in about a week — not by trying harder, but by seeing the problem clearly and making targeted adjustments.
    </p>

    <p>
      You don't need more information. You need to see your number — and then see whether you hit it.
    </p>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is it so hard to eat enough protein after 40?</h3>
        <p>Most men over 40 fail to hit their protein target because the structure of a typical day makes it almost impossible — breakfast delivers 8–12g instead of 30g, lunch is convenience-based, snacks are protein dead zones, and dinner gets overloaded in a way that biology can't compensate for. The result is 60–80g per day when most men need 120–150g.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How do I start hitting 120 grams of protein per day?</h3>
        <p>Fix one meal at a time. Start with breakfast — getting to 30g at meal one makes the rest of the day significantly easier. Then replace one low-protein snack with cottage cheese or Greek yogurt. Those two changes alone often add 40–50 grams to a typical daily total.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is a realistic daily protein intake for men over 40?</h3>
        <p>For men over 40, the research-supported target is 0.7–0.8 grams per pound of bodyweight. For a 180-pound man, that's 125–145 grams per day. Most men are currently getting 60–80 grams — which feels adequate but represents a significant daily deficit that compounds into muscle loss over time.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why does eating protein at dinner not make up for missing it earlier?</h3>
        <p>Due to anabolic resistance, older men cannot store excess protein from one meal to compensate for missed doses at earlier meals. Muscle protein synthesis requires a sufficient dose at each meal — roughly 30+ grams. Eating 70 grams at dinner triggers roughly the same response as 35–40 grams, with the excess simply burned for energy.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the easiest way to add more protein to your diet after 40?</h3>
        <p>The two highest-leverage changes: fix breakfast to hit 30g (Greek yogurt and eggs is the fastest option), and replace one low-protein snack with cottage cheese or Greek yogurt. These two changes alone can add 40–50 grams to a typical daily total without changing anything else.</p>
      </div>

